      "title": "Pursuant to Section 205 of the Federal Power Act, Part 35 of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission’s (“Commission”) regulations, and Order No. 2003, ISO New England Inc. (“ISO-NE”) and Versant Power (“Versant”) (together, the “Filing Parties”) hereby submit for filing:",
      "text": "April 15, 2026\n\nVIA ELECTRONIC FILING\n\nDebbie-Anne A. Reese, Secretary \nFederal Energy Regulatory Commission \n888 First Street, NE \nWashington, DC 20426 \n\nRE: ISO New England Inc. and Versant Power – Original Service Agreement Nos. LGIA-ISONE/VERSANT-26-01, LGIA-ISONE/VERSANT 26-02, and LGIA ISONE/VERSANT 26-03, under Schedule 22 of the ISO New England Inc.’s Open Access Transmission Tariff; Docket No. ER26-____-000\n\nDear Secretary Reese:\n\nPursuant to Section 205 of the Federal Power Act, 1 Part 35 of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission’s (“Commission”) regulations, 2 and Order No. 2003, 3 ISO New England Inc. 4 (“ISO-NE”) and Versant Power (“Versant”) (together, the “Filing Parties”) 5 hereby submit for filing:\n\n1\n\n16 U.S.C. § 824d.\n\n2\n\n18 C.F.R. Part 35.\n\n3\n\nStandardization of Generator Interconnection Agreements and Procedures, (“Order No. 2003”), FERC Stats. & Regs. ¶ 31,146 (2003), order on reh’g, (“Order No. 2003-A”), FERC Stats. & Regs. ¶ 31,160, order on reh’g, (“Order No. 2003-B”), FERC Stats. & Regs. ¶ 31,171 (2004), order on reh’g, (“Order No. 2003-C”), FERC Stats. & Regs. ¶ 31,190 (2005), aff’d sub nom. Nat’l Ass’n of Regulatory Util. Comm’rs v. FERC, 475 F.3d 1277 (D.C. Cir. 2007), cert. denied, 552 U.S. 1230, (Feb. 25, 2008).\n\n4\n\nCapitalized terms used but not defined in this filing letter have the meanings ascribed to them in the ISO New England Inc. Transmission, Markets and Services Tariff (“Tariff”). Section II of the Tariff contains the ISO-NE Open Access Transmission Tariff (“OATT”). Schedule 22 of the OATT contains the pro forma Large Generator Interconnection Procedures (“LGIP”) and Large Generator Interconnection Agreement (“LGIA”).\n\n(1) a Standard Large Generator Interconnection Agreement by and among the ISO, as the System Operator, Versant, as the Interconnecting Transmission Owner, Evergreen Wind Power III, LLC (“Evergreen III”), as the Interconnection Customer, and Evergreen Gen Lead, LCC (“Gen Lead Owner”), as the entity that will own certain Interconnection Facilities through which Evergreen III’s Large Generating Facility connects to the Administered Transmission System (“Evergreen III LGIA”); 6\n\n(2) a Standard Large Generator Interconnection Agreement by and among the ISO, as the System Operator, Versant, as the Interconnecting Transmission Owner, Stetson Holdings, LLC (“Stetson Holdings”), as the Interconnection Customer, and Evergreen Gen Lead, LCC (“Gen Lead Owner”), as the entity that will own certain Interconnection Facilities through which Stetson Holdings’ Large Generating Facility connects to the Administered Transmission System (“Stetson Holdings LGIA”); 7 and\n\n(3) a Standard Large Generator Interconnection Agreement by and among the ISO, as the System Operator, Versant, as the Interconnecting Transmission Owner, Stetson Wind II, LLC (“Stetson II”), as the Interconnection Customer, and Evergreen Gen Lead, LCC (“Gen Lead Owner”), as the entity that will own certain Interconnection Facilities through which Stetson II’s Large Generating Facility connects to the Administered Transmission System (“Stetson II LGIA”). 8\n\nAs further discussed in Section III below, the previously-effective LGIAs for the three Large Generating Facilities are being replaced as a result of 1) each Large Generating Facility reestablishing Capacity Resource Network Interconnection Service (“CNRIS”) and 2) a change in ownership for the units. The agreements, which are replacing: First Revised Service Agreement No. LGIA-ISONE/BHE-07-01; Original Service Agreement No. LGIA-ISONE/BHE-09-02, and Original Service Agreement No. LGIA-ISONE/BHE-09-03 respectively, 9 are fully executed and\n\n5\n\nSection 11.3 of the LGIP provides that “the System Operator and Interconnecting Transmission Owner shall jointly file the executed LGIA, or amendments thereto, with the Commission under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act.” Consistent with Section 11.3 of the LGIP, the Filing Parties jointly file herein the LGIAs pursuant to Section 205 of the FPA\n\n6\n\nThe Evergreen III LGIA has been designated as Original Revised Service Agreement No. LGIA ISONE/VERSANT-26-01 under the ISO Tariff.\n\n7\n\nThe Stetson Holdings LGIA has been designated as Original Service Agreement No. LGIA ISONE/VERSANT-26-02 under the ISO Tariff.\n\n8\n\nThe Evergreen III LGIA has been designated as Original Service Agreement No. LGIA ISONE/VERSANT-26-03 under the ISO Tariff.\n\n9\n\nThese agreements were filed by ISO-NE and then Transmission Owner Bangor Hydro in 2009 and accepted by the Commission in Docket No. ER09-1588. See ISO New England Inc. and Bangor Hydro-Electric Co., Docket No. ER09-1588-000 (Sept. 9, 2009) (delegated letter order).\n\nthey are non-conforming because they deviate from the pro forma LGIA in Schedule 22 of the ISO-NE OATT to reflect unique characteristics of the interconnections. Specifically, they reflect the addition of the Gen Lead Owner, an entity that owns certain Interconnection Facilities used by each Large Generating Facility.\n\nAs provided in Section III below, the Filing Parties request that the Commission accept the proposed deviations from the pro forma LGIA, as they are necessary to reflect the unique characteristics shared by each of the interconnection projects. The Filing Parties respectfully request that the Commission accept the LGIAs, as submitted, each with an effective date of, April 9, 2026, to coincide with the date that the Parties executed the LGIAs.\n\nI. DESCRIPTION OF THE FILING PARTIES; COMMUNICATIONS\n\nISO-NE is the private, non-profit entity that serves as the Regional Transmission Organization (“RTO”) for New England. ISO-NE plans and operates the New England bulk power system and administers New England’s organized wholesale electricity market pursuant to the Tariff and the Transmission Operating Agreement (“TOA”) with the New England transmission owners. In its capacity as an RTO, ISO-NE also has the objective to assure that the bulk power supply system within the New England Control Area conforms to proper standards of reliability as established by the Northeast Power Coordinating Council and the North American Electric Reliability Corporation.\n\nVersant is an electric transmission and distribution utility organized and operating under the laws of the State of Maine. Versant is engaged in the transmission and distribution of electric energy and related services to approximately 159,000 retail customers in portions of northern, eastern, and coastal Maine. Versant Power directly owns approximately 1,265 miles of transmission lines and approximately 6,090 miles of distribution lines. Versant Power also holds a 21.7 percent voting interest in Maine Electric Power Company, a transmission-only public utility. Versant is a Participating Transmission Owner (“PTO”) in ISO-NE pursuant to the terms of the TOA by and among the New England PTOs and ISO-NE.\n\nAll correspondence and communications in this proceeding should be addressed to the undersigned for ISO-NE as follows:\n\nGraham Jesmer, Esq. Senior Regulatory Counsel ISO New England Inc. One Sullivan Road Holyoke, MA 01040-2841 E-mail: gjesmer@iso-ne.com\n\nAnd to Versant as follows:\n\nJeffrey M. Jakubiak \nVinson & Elkins LLP \n1114 Avenue of the Americas, 32 nd Floor \nNew York, NY 10036 \nE-mail: JJakubiak@velaw.com \n\nII. BACKGROUND\n\nA. Description of the Interconnection Customers, the Large Generating Facilities, and Interconnection of the Large Generating Facilities to the Administered Transmission System\n\nThis filing regards three executed, non-conforming, four-party Interconnection Agreements: the Stetson Holdings, Stetson II, and Evergreen III LGIAs. Each Interconnection Customer is an indirect wholly-owned subsidiary of TerraForm Power, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“TerraForm”). 10\n\nThe Interconnection Customers’ Large Generating Facilities share a common feature. As more fully discussed below, and reflected in the Interconnection Agreements, all the Large Generating Facilities interconne",
